Piazza della Repubblica, Florence - A View On Cities|https://aviewoncities.com/florence/piazza-della-repubblica|Square of the Republic  ...    The Piazza della Repubblica was created at the end of the nineteenth century as part of an ambitious project to redevelop the historic center of Florence. Its most impressive sight is the Arcone, a triumphal arch.  ...    In 1871 the capital of Italy was moved toRome, but Florence decided to move ahead with the plans  ...    Soon, however, an international campaign was launched to protest against the project, which would result in the destruction of most of the city’s historic buildings. On top of the outrage of the public opinion across Europe, the city started to run out of funds and by 1895 the redevelopment project was brought to a standstill. By that time, the old ghetto and the Mercato Vecchio had already been razed and replaced with a spacious square, the Piazza della  ...    The most prominently visible structure on the square is the triumphal arch, known as the Arcone. It was erected in 1895 as part of the redevelopment plans. An inscription on
